description:
English digital chapters for the Bad Break graphic novel.

A classic crime story peppered with plenty of noir tropes and dark humor. A determined antique dealer, a bored junkyard worker, and an inquisitive porn star join forces as they follow the tortuous trail of a long-dead sailor. Written and drawn by Philippe Riche ( The Alliance of the Curious ) in his trademark loose yet graceful line.
name: Bad Break

description:
English digital chapters for the Beirut 1990: Snapshots of A Civil War graphic novel.

The travel diary of two brothers to a land at war. 1990, off to join an aunt working for a relief organization, young Frenchmen Sylvain and Bruno Ricard come to discover the ins and outs of everyday life in Lebanon's war-torn capital. More than a decade later, the brothers recount their experiences with the help of artist Christophe Gaultier, as inspired by the real life pictures taken by the siblings on their journey of discovery.
name: Beirut 1990: Snapshots of A Civil War

description:
There once was a jungle so immense it would engulf even the greatest city skyscrapers. Within it, life flourished on a grand scale with millions of animals and a handful of hominid species calling it home. Chief among them, were two warring tribes, the Humans and Neanderthals.

While the Neanderthals lived closely with nature and thrived in the treetops, the Humans secluded themselves in a decaying city atop a lonely Mountain. The divide between the two tribes changes forever when, one day, a carefree young Neanderthal named Keyli, and the woman he loved - an albino named Sno - happened upon a young Human named Icari, lost in the jungle.
name: Hominids

description: A psychopath wakes up in an asylum and must become a monster hunter during the Apocalypse, but he doesn't know if he's in the Apocalypse, killing people and thinks it's the Apocalypse, or it's all in his head the whole time.
name: Ichabod Jones: Monster Hunter

description:
From video game star to comic strip hero!

At the end of his 1993 Super Nintendo game, Plok fell asleep in his comfy chair. All of his enemies were defeated, and all of his precious flags were back in place. Twenty years later he wakes up in a comic strip, not quite sure where he is, what year it is, or why he never got a sequel.

The Pickford Bros, creators of the original Plok video game, have revived their creation in the form of a weekly web-based comic strip.

Each comic strip following Plok as he wakes up and rediscovers the world he inhabits, meeting old adversaries from the SNES game and making new friends from elsewhere in the world of video games.
name: Plok

description:
Proper Japanese Title: グランドジャンプPREMIUM

Grand Jump Premium launched a few weeks after Grand Jump as a companion magazine. However, where Grand Jump was a consolidation of the Super Jump and Business Jump markets, Grand Jump Premium was the place most of these orphaned series were allowed to continue. Over a dozen serials were transferred from these two magazines in the first two issues of Premium.

Originally begun as a monthly magazine, this title was a rarity among Shueisha manga anthologies as it used a proper sequential numbering (the norm with American comics). However, in early 2014, the series' took a brief hiatus after 26 volumes before returning, now using the more common YYYYMM numbering and soon slowing down to a bimonthly release schedule.

Grand Jump and Grand Jump Premium do share a lot of the same series, with a number of them having transferred from one to the other (both directions).

Serials from the magazine include:

  • Bin: Sonshi Iden
  • Faust
  • Jigoku Sensei Nūbē Neo
  • Kuchiireya Kyouji
  • Love Karma
  • Magi no Okurimono
  • Ōsama no Shitateya: Sartoria Napoletana
  • Reibaishi Izuna: Ascension
name: Grand Jump Premium

description:
Proper Japanese Title: ザ マーガレット

Spin-off of Margaret, initially it was published irregularly from 1982-1989 and though its publishing rate has changed multiple times over the decades it is usually bimonthly. Though it does have some of its own original serials (often not very long), it is primarily a playground for creators to publish one-shots.

Serials from this magazine include:

  • @Kiraki Lovers!
  • Hakushaku to Yōsei
name: The Margaret

description:
Proper Japanese Title: オフィスユー

Office You is a monthly spin-off of You. It debuted a year before Young You, the better-known spin-off magazine, but has since outlasted that franchise. Interestingly, since You slowed down its publishing rate in 2011 from twice a month to once a month, it is now published at the same frequency as Office You (a rarity among spin-off magazines, which are generally published at a slower rate than their parent). It manages to keep an audience at a size similar to You, and outsells a number of better-known ongoing magazines at Shueisha.

Serials from this magazine include:

  • Do Da Dancin'! Venice Kokusaihen
name: Office You
